{
  "doc_id": "36235",
  "text": "For each of the 60 combinations of distribution, success proportion, and runs size, 100,000 simulated runs were generated using the specified distribution. From these simulated runs, 1,000 samples of the specified number of runs were randomly selected. For each sample the 95% confidence interval for the sample's computational effort was calculated using Wilson's method. Whether the confidence interval included the true computational effort (the coverage) was recorded. Although the average coverage for Left-Triangle dips to 91.1%, this should be compared to Robert Newcombe's analysis of the performance of the normal-approximation method for confidence intervals for a proportion [CITATION_1] . He showed that method to have an estimated mean coverage of 88%. In that light, Wilson's method on the Left-Triangle data performs better than that generally-accepted and widely used method.",
